  "notes": "Interlingue (originally Occidental), constructed international auxiliary language published by Edgar de Wahl in 1922; renamed Interlingue in 1949. Published, fully regular phonemic orthography over the 26-letter Latin alphabet. Softening rules: ⟨c⟩ = [ts] before e/i/y and [k] elsewhere; ⟨g⟩ = [ʒ] before e/i/y and [ɡ] elsewhere; intervocalic ⟨s⟩ = [z]. ⟨ch⟩ = [ʃ], ⟨j⟩ = [ʒ], ⟨z⟩ = [dz], ⟨y⟩ = [j] as a consonant and [i] as a vowel. Stress falls on the vowel before the final consonant; the endings -bil, -ic, -im, -ul, -um are ignored for stress; irregular stress is marked with an acute accent (café, ímpossibil), so the accented vowels map to the same qualities as their unaccented counterparts.",
